nking crash of 2008, the subsequent recession, as well as UN peacekeeping and the ongoing Egyptian revolution. Each case study highlights the gritty experiences of women in diverse circumstances—in banks, on the job market, in war zones, and in revolutions. The results of taking women seriously are fresh insights into what fuels the cultures of hyper–risk taking, of sexual harassment, and the denial of women’s post-war security.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFeminism. 0aFeminist theory. 0aFinancial crises. 0aMale domination (Social structure). 0aWomen. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  a2008.  aamerica.  aanthropology.  abanking crash.  abanking.  acase studies.  acultural criticism.  acurrent events.  adominique strauss kahn.  aegyptian revolution.  afemale experience.  afeminism.  afeminist theory.  agender dynamics.  agender politics.  agender studies.  ajob market.  amodern women.  anonfiction.  apostwar era.  arecession.  arevolutionary women.  arevolutions.  arisk taking.  aseriousness.  asexual harassment.  ataken seriously.  aun peacekeeping.  awar zones.  awomens issues.  awomens security.  aworth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027537940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095666740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956667423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520956667/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY